The Pain Point Analysis model is created to analyze a business process or product that is problematic and leading to stakeholder dissatisfaction. It may or may not be a real problem but is perceived as an obstacle that hinders the process customer or stakeholder from finding a solution. Pain Point Analysis is a useful tool when assessing the current state performance of a business process and seeking to identify areas to focus remediation activity based on the likely return on effort. Pain Point analysis should focus on the problem identification and extent of condition which can be input to the problem statement creation. When to Use Pain Point Analysis Pain Point Analysis is a useful tool when assessing the current state performance of a business process and seeking to identify areas to focus remediation activity based on the likely return on effort. In other words, where will improvement time and resources reduce the most process pain. Effective use of the method is reliant on having stakeholders with suitable knowledge of process' current performance as well as the availability of relevant process performance data (e.g. volumes, error rates} Why Use Pain Point Analysis Typically, processes will under perform across a range of areas - and a structured method for determining where to prioritize effort is critical to any process improvement exercise. Using Pain Point Analysis, a business analyst can guide an organization to agree on where maximum pain is being experienced and therefore where it is most essential to focus improvement effort and resources. Following Pain Point Analysis, Solution Ideation and Assessment are used to asses effort, feasibility and risk of solutions. Some Examples of Pain Areas that will be generated as part of a pain point analysis are:  
  1. Particular processes takes too long, which inhibits productivity. Current solutions waste too much time with minimal results.
  2. Spending too much money on their current solutions and they are either looking to save money, or get a better bang for their buck.
  3. Process where locating, procuring, and assembling all of the items needed takes longer than the value added part of the process.
For this model we defined a problem as a persistent or recurring event that frequently inconveniences or annoys process customers and/or stakeholders. The pain point analysis model pattern was created to provide several analysis diagrams that can be systematically used to identify and show the pain points, gaps, plusses, and deltas that stakeholders want to be fixed, from the perspective of each stakeholder. The model was generated through a series of workshops with multiple representatives for each stakeholder interactively providing input. The brainstorming workshops were systematically held with each workshop focusing on one of the model sections in the following order:  
  1. Completed the "Stakeholder Brainstorm"- who are the stakeholders of the process/product of interest.
  2. Completed the "Pain Point Brain Storm Canvas" for each stakeholder group by having a Pain Point Brainstorming workshop where the plusses, deltas, pain points, and gaps were generated.
  3. Completed the"Pain Point Analysis" with the stakeholder groups to rank and group pain points by occurrence and impact to the stakeholder
  4. Compile the results using the "Pain Point Analysis Report"

SWOT Analysis is a simple but useful framework for analyzing your organization's strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats. It helps you to build on what you do well, to address what you're lacking, to minimize risks, and to take the greatest possible advantage of chances
A SWOT analysis is a way of understanding the Strengths and Weaknesses of your schools; the Opportunities that might be available; and the Threats that they might face. You can conduct a SWOT analysis with a variety of school stakeholders (parents, board members, staff and students etc.) but, generally, you would do this with management staff and board members. You use a SWOT analysis to identify the critical issues for your organization (the weaknesses and threats); and to explore strategies for improvement. Your strengths allow you to craft a strategy that helps distinguish you from your competitors, opportunities provide information that allows you to exploit conditions within your school or area, and information on weaknesses and threats helps you to manage and/or eliminate things that may endanger your school operations.
If you use a SWOT analysis as a serious tool to inform your strategic direction then the analysis of each of the SWOT areas needs to be rigorous and based on accurate, verifiable statements. That is, answers to questions should rely on hard data rather than opinion. For example, 'a strength of the school is our academic results' is not precise, whereas 87% of our students perform above state benchmarks' is. It is also important when using SWOT analysis as a serious tool that you ruthlessly prune items identified so that you spend most of your time in analyzing significant strengths, weaknesses, opportunities and threats, rather than those things that do not seriously impact on the viability of the school.

Root Cause Analysis (RCA) is a comprehensive term encompassing a collection of problem solving methods used to identify the real cause of a non-conformance or quality problem. Root Cause Analysis is the process of defining, understanding and solving a problem. The root cause has also been described as an underlying or fundamental cause of a non-conformance, defect or failure. Furthermore, the term “root cause” can also be referred to as the precise point in the causal chain where applying a corrective action or intervention would prevent the non-conformance from occurring. Repeat problems are a source of waste in manufacturing. Waste in the form of machine downtime, product rework, increased scrap and the time and resources spent “fixing” the problem. Many times we may believe that the problem is resolved but in reality we have just addressed a symptom of the problem and not the actual root cause. Correctly performed, a Root Cause Analysis can identify breakdowns in your processes or systems that contributed to the non-conformance and determine how to prevent it from happening again. An RCA is performed to identify what happened, why it happened and then determine what improvements or changes are required. Through the proper application of RCA, repeat problems can be eliminated. RCA methods and tools are not limited to manufacturing process problems only. Many industries are applying RCA methodology in various situations and are using this structured approach to problem solving. Some examples of where RCA is being used include, but are not limited to:  
  1. Office Processes and Procedures
  2. Quality Control Problems
  3. Healthcare Incident Analysis
  4. Safety-based Situations or Accident Analysis
  5. Failure Analysis in Engineering and Maintenance
  6. Change Management or Continuous Improvement Activities
  7. Computer Systems or Software Analysis
The point is that RCA can be applied to almost any type of problem that companies face every day. Another example where RCA could be used is for a company that is experiencing a high level of incorrect customer orders and shipments. The process can be mapped, analyzed and the root cause (s) of the problems can be identified and resolved. The end result is a happy, loyal customer-base and lower overall cost to the company. Root Cause Analysis (RCA) is usually a step in a larger problem solving exercise. There are multiple tools that may be used during a Root Cause Analysis. Some of them can sometimes be completed by one person, but in most cases a Cross Functional Team (CFT) approach will reap the greatest benefits and increase chances of reaching the true “root cause”.

The stakeholder view is used to help us understand the concerns, responsibilities, and goals of all the critical stakeholders. The stakeholder model helps us to understand what each stakeholder is concerned about and how to deliver on those goals ensuring that their concerns are covered. This package contains several tools that systematically identify and analyze stakeholder's perspectives of the system. The packages that are contained in this stakeholder analysis model are:  
  1. Detailed Stakeholder Analysis- which is used for individual stakeholder analysis of concerns, goals, responsibilities.
  1. Project Stakeholder Views- which is used for analysis of the stakeholders influence and effect on the project.
Why is it important to address? What is the impact to he customer and the organization.
What is the Problem that needs to be solved? Describe the issue being experienced or needing corrected.
What are the symptoms associated with the problem?
Where/when is the problem occurring? What is the context situation, process in which the problem exists?
When was the problem first observed?
Who has the problem? Internal or external customer?
How often is the problem observed?

The pain points package contains the description of individual pain points identified during the analysis. Specific details as to the nature of the pain point and effects are summarized for each pain point. A pain point is a specific problem that prospective stakeholder (or customers) of your system are experiencing. In other words, pain points are problems told from the prospective of you stakeholders themselves. The following template shows the best practice used for documenting this element when further clarification was need and what each section contains: Pain#- Name PAIN POINT DESCRIPTION Provide a brief description of the pain point and why it is a pain point vs a delta which is something that could be done better. CONTEXT Provide a brief description of the context in which the pain point is encountered or contributes to the overall problem IMPACT Describe the impact of the pain point, such as the entire process breaks down, or the entire solution path is blocked.

Pluses are the items that the individual or team wants to maintain and build upon. The Plusses package is different from the other packages in this model because it contains the positive elements associated with product or process. The Plusses package contains all of the plusses or things that the process/product is doing well. The following template shows the best practice used for documenting this element when further clarification was need and what each section contains: Plus#- Name DESCRIPTION Provide a brief description of the plus and why it is beneficial. CONTEXT Provide a brief description of the context in which the plus is encountered or contributes.

The Deltas Package contains negative elements of the process/product. These are different from pains in the sense that pains are smaller in scope and more fact based. The following template shows the best practice used for documenting this element when further clarification was need and what each section contains: Delta##- Name Deltas name should be action oriented and begin with a verb. DESCRIPTION Identify the opportunity for improvement by including things that can be changed so that the individual or team may be more effective in a concise manner. CONTEXT Some brief context should be provided that gives:
  1. Deltas should be specific in how/when they occur
  2. Deltas should be within the realm of possibility
  3. Deltas should be reviewed and acted upon

A stakeholder analysis helps you identify which stakeholders are being impacted by a change project, where each stands on receptiveness to the change, and which ones can impact a change project the most. Stakeholder assessment is a critical component of effective business change management because it increases the success of your stakeholder engagement and management.

SWOT Analysis is a simple but useful framework for analyzing your organization's strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and threats. It helps you to build on what you do well, to address what you're lacking, to minimize risks, and to take the greatest possible advantage of chances
A SWOT analysis is a way of understanding the Strengths and Weaknesses of your schools; the Opportunities that might be available; and the Threats that they might face. You can conduct a SWOT analysis with a variety of school stakeholders (parents, board members, staff and students etc.) but, generally, you would do this with management staff and board members. You use a SWOT analysis to identify the critical issues for your organization (the weaknesses and threats); and to explore strategies for improvement. Your strengths allow you to craft a strategy that helps distinguish you from your competitors, opportunities provide information that allows you to exploit conditions within your school or area, and information on weaknesses and threats helps you to manage and/or eliminate things that may endanger your school operations.
If you use a SWOT analysis as a serious tool to inform your strategic direction then the analysis of each of the SWOT areas needs to be rigorous and based on accurate, verifiable statements. That is, answers to questions should rely on hard data rather than opinion. For example, 'a strength of the school is our academic results' is not precise, whereas 87% of our students perform above state benchmarks' is. It is also important when using SWOT analysis as a serious tool that you ruthlessly prune items identified so that you spend most of your time in analyzing significant strengths, weaknesses, opportunities and threats, rather than those things that do not seriously impact on the viability of the school.

Threats:
  1. Are there any threats to the school community that might affect viability (e.g. financial, infrastructure,
  2. things your competition is doing)?
  3. What dangers might the school be exposed to because of changes to government policy?
  4. What risks/ obstacles do you face?
Identifying threats helps you to manage and/or eliminate things that may endanger your school operations.

Strengths:
  1. What advantages does your school have?
  2. What does your school do better than other schools?
  3. What makes your school unique'?
  4. What does your school community see as your strengths?
  5. What do staff members see as your strengths?
Consider your strengths from both internal and external perspective - and be honest and realistic. It is useful to think about your strengths in relation to other schools. If you do exactly what the schools in your area do, even if what you do is very good, it is not a strength but rather a necessity for you to compete with other schools. Your strengths are what give you a competitive advantage.

Opportunities:
  1. What strengths can you exploit to increase your competitive advantage?
  2. What is happening in education that might be a good opportunity for the school?
  3. What opportunities might technology give us?
  4. What are the unique elements in our community that might provide opportunities?
  5. What is missing from the school! community that might be an opportunity for US?
  6. What weaknesses might we eliminate to create opportunities?
Identifying opportunities provides information that allows you exploit conditions within your school or community.

Weaknesses:
  1. What are the disadvantages your school has compared with other schools?
  2. What could be improved?
  3. What are people within your community likely to see as weaknesses?
  4. What are people within your school likely to see as weaknesses?
  5. What factors lose you enrolments'?
Information about your weaknesses helps you to manage and/or eliminate things that may endanger your school operations. Again, consider this from internal and external perspectives. And, again, be honest and realistic. In particular, consider your school against your competitors. Are your competitors getting more enrolments/losing fewer students? In which areas do they appear to be doing better than you? Why might this be the case?

The Problem Before RCA can be performed, the problem must be well defined. The following information must be determined and documented:
Who discovered the problem? What exactly happened? Where in the process was the problem discovered? When was the problem discovered? How many / How often does it happen? How was the problem detected? Next, the team may want to collect data or other additional information. It may also be necessary to initiate interim containment or corrective actions. The team should review all gathered information and further define the problem. The problem should be defined based on facts and data. Once the problem is fully described the team can then begin the Root Cause Analysis phase.

UML:TaggedValue.value: The Problem Definition Canvas was used to systematically craft the problem statement. This diagram is intended to be a concise description of the problem statement. What Is a Problem Statement? A problem is a statement about an area of concern, a condition to be improved upon, a difficulty to be eliminated, or a troubling question that exists in theory or in practice that points to the need for meaningful understanding and deliberate investigation. For more details: https://www.isixsigma.com/new-to-six-sigma/getting-started/how-to-write-an-effective-problem-statement/

The Pain Point Brainstorm Canvas illustrates the different pains that the stakeholders are experiencing with respect to the problem and the problem statement. This diagram also shows the pluses or positive things that are being experienced now and the deltas or experiences that need to be eliminated or improved upon.
The pain point brainstorm canvas was created to captured the current lay of the land with regard to the business process/product being analyzed. A pain point brainstorm was created for each of the stakeholders from their perspective.
The pain point analysis also combine the common Plus - Delta analysis tool because the brainstorming workshops often generate discussion elements which identify what is going well and what needs to be changed. This tool asks participants to reflect on their continuous improvement and inform the changes needed to achieve higher performance. The Plus Delta inclusion involved drawing two additional areas in the analysis diagram, where one represents the positive feedback (what the group thinks went well) and the other represents the negative feedback (what the group thinks didn't go well and needs improvement).

Pain Point Analysis is a method for assessing the issues impacting the performance of a business process by considering the relative weighting of process issues across two dimensions. The analyst can choose the most relevant dimensions, however a typical combination is impact or severity combined with volume or frequency. An alternate to volume / frequency in some situations is delectability. The Pain Point Analysis diagram illustrates the impact that the different pains have on the process and that the stakeholders are experiencing with respect to the problem and the problem statement.
This diagram is to clearly reveal which pains needs to be addressed. Typically the Pain Points that are in the top right quadrants should be the highest priority to resolve.

The Stakeholder Support Map shows the two primary variables used to quantify stakeholder impacts on a project, their Influence and Power. The stakeholder's power is the ability of the stakeholder to change or stop the project. While the interest is the amount of involvement the stakeholder has in the project.
The Stakeholder Management Levels Diagram shows the ranking of rht stakeholders and where their investment in the project needs to be to show that the project is successful.

The Stakeholder Onion Diagram is stakeholder analysis tool from the arsenal of project management. It is used to display the relationships of stakeholders to a project which has a set of gaols. The Onion Diagram shows how stakeholder activities affect project results and depict how the relationships that subsist in a project environment can influence on a project. A set of libraries and objects provided by this solution make short work of visualizing the stakeholder analysis of a project. Some things to consider when applying this pattern: Knowledge Area: Business Analysis Planning & Monitoring Applicable Task: Conduct Stakeholder Analysis Useful When: Identifying stakeholders involved in your project. Helps the BA determine which stakeholders will directly interact with a system or process and those outside the organization. Layer 1: Stakeholders closely involved in the creation of the product, which could be a new system or a new process. Stakeholders may include the project manager, software developer, business analyst, etc Layer 2: Stakeholders whose work changes when the solution is defined. For example, end users. Layer 3: Sponsors, executives and subject matter experts who interact closely with the system Layer 4: External Stakeholders such as customers, regulators, government, suppliers and the like.
The Stakeholder Hierarchy Diagram shows the hierarchy of the stakeholders for the project and the system.

The Ishikawa or Fishbone Diagram is a useful tool in determining the most likely causes (MLCs) of a quality problem. The diagram is sometimes referred to as a Fishbone Diagram because it looks much like a skeleton of a fish with the effect or problem being listed in a box at the end. The main sections of the diagram are used to address the 6Ms (Man, Material, Method, Machine, Measurement and Mother Nature (Environment). The diagrams are usually worked right to left, with each large “bone” of the fish branching out to include smaller bones with additional details. It is important not to limit the teams brainstorming ideas here. If an idea is in a different section of the diagram, simply list it in the appropriate section and then go back to it later. Once the team has brainstormed all the possible causes of the problem, the team should rate the potential causes according to their level of importance and likelihood of contributing to the failure and develop a hierarchy. From the hierarchy the team should select which causes to further investigate. Root cause analysis (RCA) is a structured team process that assists in identifying underlying factors or causes of an adverse event or near-miss. Understanding the contributing factors or potential causes of a system failure can help develop actions that sustain the corrective actions. It is important that RCAs are completed in a structured and methodical manner starting at the top system level then work down to sub-systems and eventually arriving at causes within components and modules. Systematic evaluation of RCAs ensures that the true underlying cause has been arrived such that any resulting corrective actions are holistic addressing the full scope of the root cause. FISHBONE ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS DIAGRAM At the start of an RCA is it is important to initially organize potential causes in a cause and effect diagram. One diagram type is called a “fishbone” diagram. Fishbone diagrams can help in brainstorming to identify possible causes of a problem and in sorting ideas into useful categories. A fishbone diagram is a visual way to look at cause and effect. It is a more structured approach than some other tools available for brainstorming causes of a problem. A fishbone diagram can be helpful in identifying possible causes for a problem that might not otherwise be considered by directing the team to look at the categories and think of alternative causes. At the beginning of the Fishbone activity it is important to arrive at a measurable problem statement that has been observed. The problem or effect is then displayed at the head or mouth of the fish. Possible contributing causes are listed on the smaller “bones” under various cause categories. As potential causes from lower levels of the system and/or sub-systems are exposed it might become necessary to add child bones to a main a bone in the diagram to capture those causes in relation to their appropriate sub-system. Upon completion of the fishbone activity it is necessary to review the potential causes and prioritize which ones to investigate. This can be done with several different method, the most common being dot voting by the subject matter experts. A Best Practice is to continually review and update the fishbone diagram by visually showing (color coding or use of graphics) to show which potential causes have been proven or discredited in contributing to the root cause.

<font color="#dc143c">The “Is/Is Not” analysis may be used at different points in the RCA. It can be used while defining the problem to determine what is in scope and will be considered during the analysis and what is out of scope and will not be considered. It can also be used when planning a solution, to help the team decide what to include and what to exclude. The Is-Is Not analysis allows the team to think about the problem and the boundaries of what it is or is not. The tool helps the team maintain their focus. If the boundary of the problem is not clearly defined the team may stray off the initial path and work on solving inconsequential problems.</font> <font color="#dc143c"> </font><font color="#dc143c">Document what “Is” and “Is Not” part of or a characteristic of the problem. The process works by asking the team various questions such as:</font> <font color="#dc143c"> </font><font color="#dc143c">Who is impacted by this problem?</font> <font color="#dc143c">Does the team have the authority to resolve this issue?</font> <font color="#dc143c">What do we already know about the problem?</font> <font color="#dc143c">Is this something that will impact the customer?</font> <font color="#dc143c">Will we actually do something about this?</font> <font color="#dc143c">Ask the team enough questions until there is a clear definition of the problem / scope of the problem solving process.</font>
